    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Solve the equation</p>
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + \cot t \cdot y = \sin t.\]
<p>\(y = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] \(\displaystyle + \frac{C}{\sin t}\) [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>This is a linear differential equation that is already in standard form.
    Note that here \(f(t) = \cot t\) and \(g(t) = \sin t\).
</p>
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + \cot t \cdot y = \sin t.\]
<p>We use the key point to find the integrating factor:</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
    \text{I.F.} &amp;= \exp \left[ \int \cot t \,\mathrm{d}t \right] \\
                &amp;= \exp \left[ \int \frac{\cos t}{\sin t} \,\mathrm{d}t \right] \\
                &amp;= \exp [ \ln (\sin t) ] \\
                &amp;= \sin t
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Next we transform the equation into exact form by multiplying both sides with the
    integrating factor. It becomes:
</p>
\[\sin t \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + \cos t \cdot y = \sin^2 t\]
<p>Note that the left-hand side is the derivative of \(\sin t \cdot y\) with respect to \(t\).
    Our equation then becomes:
</p>
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t} \left( \sin t \cdot y \right) = \sin^2 t\]
<p>Therefore, we can find an expression for \(\sin t \cdot y\) by integrating the right-hand side.
    The result is:
</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
    \sin t \cdot y &amp;= \int \sin^2 t \,\mathrm{d}t \\
                   &amp;= \int (1 - \cos^2 t) \,\mathrm{d}t \\
                   &amp;= \int \left(1 - \frac{1 + \cos(2t)}{2}\right) \,\mathrm{d}t \\
                   &amp;= \int \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{\cos(2t)}{2}\right) \,\mathrm{d}t \\
                   &amp;= \frac{t}{2} - \frac{\sin(2t)}{4} + C
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Which then gives the following general solution:</p>
\[y = \frac{t}{2\sin t} - \frac{\sin(2t)}{4\sin t} + \frac{C}{\sin t}\]]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
